Yes, people still live near the Rabaul volcano after the eruption. The town of Rabaul and its surrounding communities were rebuilt after the 1994 eruption, although many of the buildings and infrastructure were damaged or destroyed. 

Despite the risk posed by living near an active volcano, the area remains home to a significant population, and many people rely on the surrounding land for their livelihoods, including agriculture and fishing. The local authorities continue to monitor the volcano and have plans in place to evacuate the area if necessary.
